1 (II) A RAILROAD COMPANY SHALL MONITOR THE RESPONSE OF
2 THE RAILROAD COMPANY’S EMPLOYEES TO ALERTS RECEIVED FROM WAYSIDE
3 DETECTOR SYSTEMS AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IF AN EMPLOYEE FAILS TO
4 TAKE THE REQUIRED COURSE OF ACTION.
5 (D) THE COMMISSIONER SHALL ESTABLISH A PROCESS FOR CERTIFYING
6 THAT EACH RAILROAD COMPANY HAS INSTALLED WAYSIDE DETECTOR SYSTEMS ON
7 TRACKS IN THE STATE AS REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION.
8 (E) (1) THE COMMISSIONER SHALL INVESTIGATE ALLEGED VIOLATIONS
9 OF THIS SECTION.
10 (2) (I) IF THE COMMISSIONER DETERMINES THAT A RAILROAD
11 COMPANY HAS VIOLATED THIS SECTION OR VIOLATED REGULATIONS ADOPTED BY
12 THE COMMISSIONER UNDER THIS SECTION, THE COMMISSIONER SHALL ISSUE A
13 WRITTEN REPORT TO THE RAILROAD COMPANY:
14 1. DETAILING THE REASONS FOR FINDING THAT A
15 VIOLATION HAS OCCURRED; AND
16 2. ORDERING THE RAILROAD COMPANY TO CORRECT
17 THE VIOLATION WITHIN 60 DAYS AFTER THE REPORT IS ISSUED.
18 (II) IF THE COMMISSIONER ISSUES A REPORT UNDER
19 SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH, THE COMMISSIONER SHALL SUBMIT THE
20 REPORT TO THE GOVERNOR AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
21 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY.
22 (F) (1) A RAILROAD COMPANY THAT FAILS TO CORRECT A VIOLATION
23 WITHIN 60 DAYS AFTER ISSUANCE OF A REPORT BY THE COMMISSIONER UNDER
24 SUBSECTION (E) OF THIS SECTION IS SUBJECT TO A CIVIL FINE NOT EXCEEDING
25 $10,000 TO BE ASSESSED BY THE COMMISSIONER.
26 (2) EACH DAY THAT THE PERSON FAILS TO CORRECT A VIOLATION
27 AFTER THE 60–DAY PERIOD SHALL CONSTITUTE A SEPARATE VIOLATION.
28 (G) THE COMMISSIONER SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT THIS
29 SECTION.
